  <h1>DTAA India-Singapore: a practical guide</h1>
  <div class="byline">
    <span class="av">SR</span><b>Written by a Chartered Accountant</b>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>NumberIQ Editorial</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>7 min read</span>
  </div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>The India-Singapore DTAA caps tax on cross-border dividends, interest, royalties and fees for technical services, and includes a limitation-of-benefits (LOB) clause.</b> Following the 2016-17 protocol, capital gains on shares acquired from 1 April 2017 are taxable in the source state, ending the earlier residence-based exemption.</p>

  <div class="toc"><b>On this page</b><a href="#s0">Treaty rates (illustrative)</a> &middot; <a href="#s1">Capital gains: the 2017 shift</a> &middot; <a href="#s2">Limitation of benefits (LOB)</a> &middot; <a href="#s3">Practical points</a></div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 1 — activate after approval -->

  <h2 id="s0">Treaty rates (illustrative)</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Income</th><th>India-Singapore treaty cap (illustrative)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Dividends</td><td>10%-15%</td></tr><tr><td>Interest</td><td>10%-15%</td></tr><tr><td>Royalty</td><td>10%</td></tr><tr><td>Fees for technical services</td><td>10%</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Rates are indicative; <span class="verify">VERIFY</span> the exact article, rate and any conditions before applying.</p>

  <h2 id="s1">Capital gains: the 2017 shift</h2>
<p>Historically, capital gains on Indian shares were taxable only in Singapore (residence state), making it a favoured route. The <b>2016-17 protocol</b> aligned the treaty with the revised India-Mauritius position: shares <b>acquired on or after 1 April 2017</b> are taxable in the <b>source state (India)</b>, with a grandfathering of earlier acquisitions. This curtailed treaty-shopping for capital gains.</p>

  <h2 id="s2">Limitation of benefits (LOB)</h2>
<p>The treaty contains an <b>LOB clause</b> requiring genuine substance &mdash; a Singapore resident must not be a shell or conduit and must meet expenditure/listing tests to access benefits. Combined with the <b>MLI principal-purpose test</b>, this means treaty benefits depend on real commercial substance in Singapore, not mere incorporation.</p>

  <h2 id="s3">Practical points</h2>
<ul><li>Maintain a <b>TRC</b>, Form 10F and substance evidence for the Singapore entity.</li><li>Check LOB expenditure thresholds before claiming benefits.</li><li>Apply the more beneficial of the Act or treaty rate for <a href="tds-non-resident-section-195-guide.html">Section 195</a> withholding.</li><li>Coordinate with <a href="transfer-pricing-india-guide.html">transfer pricing</a> for related-party flows.</li></ul>

  <div class="faq">
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>Are capital gains on Indian shares taxable under the India-Singapore treaty?</summary><p>For shares acquired on or after 1 April 2017, yes &mdash; they are taxable in the source state (India) following the 2016-17 protocol; earlier acquisitions are grandfathered.</p></details>
    <details><summary>What is the LOB clause?</summary><p>A limitation-of-benefits provision that denies treaty benefits to shell or conduit entities lacking genuine substance, with expenditure and other tests to qualify.</p></details>
    <details><summary>What rate applies to royalties under the treaty?</summary><p>Around 10% under the treaty, but apply the more beneficial of the Act or DTAA rate and confirm the exact article before deducting.</p></details>
  </div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 2 — activate after approval -->

  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2>
    <ul><li>Treaty caps dividends/interest/royalty/FTS; FTS around 10%.</li><li>Share gains: source taxation for acquisitions from 1 April 2017.</li><li>LOB clause requires genuine Singapore substance.</li><li>MLI principal-purpose test reinforces the substance requirement.</li></ul>
  </div>

